AGI - It must be done quickly and with immediate interventions to cope with the drought in Sicily >. The cost of short-term actions deemed necessary by the regional government is 130 million euros, while for medium-term actions it is 590 million euros. "The drought in Sicily is becoming dramatic." The Region - says Governor Renato Schifani - has already put in place a series of actions to mitigate the crisis, helping the productive sectors and limiting the inconvenience to the citizens, but also serve urgent state interventions to operate on networks and systems of water supply and to sensitize the citizens to a more rational use of the resource".
&nbsp;
The regional executive called for the state of national emergency for the water crisis. A decision taken during the last Junta as a result of the long drought and the significant reduction of water reserves throughout the region. The aim of the measure, which must now be approved by the Council of Ministers, is to ensure drinking water to citizens and water supply to the agricultural and zootechnical sectors, as well as to companies engaged in the yards of the island.&nbsp;&nbsp; "It is necessary - says Schifani - tax reliefs and contributions, moratories and suspension of compliance for the enterprises of the agricultural and zootechnical sector that are in grave difficulty".
&nbsp;
A report of the Civil Protection >regional indicates short and medium-term interventions to mitigate the crisis that preview the reduction of the consumption of the hydropowers, interventions on the invaders, information campaigns and sensitization for the saving, interventions in order to find alternative resources (such as mobile dissalators and ships with dissalative modules), purchase of autobotti and silos for the distribution in public places, use of wells and springs, repair of networks
&nbsp;
The region, in the past few weeks, had already declared the state of water crisis both for drinking and for agricultural-zootechnical use, appointing also two commissioners. For the productive sectors concerned, the procedures for measures for approximately € 5.5 million were initiated, which provide for reductions from the fees of remediation consortia and administrative simplification measures. A regional observatory on water uses has also been set up to constantly monitor the state of invaders and water reserves.

